Appendix A: Mathematical Background

This appendix collects the essential mathematical definitions and results used throughout the thesis. All spaces, operations, and properties are stated in a self‑contained manner.

A.1 Formal Grammars and Languages

A context‑free grammar is a quadruple G = (N, \Sigma, R, S) where:

· N is a finite set of nonterminal symbols,
· \Sigma is a finite set of terminal symbols,
· R \subseteq N \times (N \cup \Sigma)^* is a finite set of production rules,
· S \in N is the start symbol.

For a rule A \to \alpha we write A \Rightarrow \alpha. The language generated by G is

\mathcal{L}(G) = \{ w \in \Sigma^* \mid S \Rightarrow^* w \},

where \Rightarrow^* denotes the reflexive transitive closure of \Rightarrow.

A typed grammar assigns to each symbol a type (e.g., scalar, vector, tensor) and a dimension vector \dim \in \mathbb{Z}^7 representing the exponents in the seven SI base dimensions. Production rules must satisfy type compatibility: for an operator f with arity k, there exist a type transformation \phi_f and a dimension transformation \psi_f such that if the arguments have types \tau_1,\dots,\tau_k and dimensions d_1,\dots,d_k, then the resulting expression has type \phi_f(\tau_1,\dots,\tau_k) and dimension \psi_f(d_1,\dots,d_k).

A.2 Trees and Tree‑Edit Distance

An expression tree is a rooted ordered tree where each node is labeled by a symbol from N \cup \Sigma, and the children of a node labeled with a nonterminal correspond to the right‑hand side of a production. The depth of a tree is the length of the longest path from the root to a leaf.

The tree‑edit distance d(T_1, T_2) is the minimum cost of a sequence of node insertions, deletions, and replacements that transforms T_1 into T_2, where each operation has unit cost. This defines a metric on the set of all trees. When applied to expression trees, we first map them to a canonical form \mathcal{S}(T) using a confluent and terminating rewriting system that orders commutative operands, folds constants, and removes identity operations. The distance is then computed on the canonical forms.

A.3 Hilbert and Sobolev Spaces

Let \Omega \subset \mathbb{R}^n be a bounded domain with Lipschitz boundary. For a function f : \Omega \to \mathbb{R}^m, the L^2 norm is

\|f\|_{L^2(\Omega)} = \left( \int_\Omega \|f(x)\|^2 \, dx \right)^{1/2},

where \|\cdot\| is the Euclidean norm on \mathbb{R}^m. The space L^2(\Omega;\mathbb{R}^m) of square‑integrable functions is a Hilbert space with inner product \langle f,g\rangle = \int_\Omega f(x)^T g(x)\,dx.

For an integer k \ge 0, the Sobolev space H^k(\Omega;\mathbb{R}^m) consists of functions whose weak derivatives up to order k exist and belong to L^2. The norm is

\|f\|_{H^k} = \left( \sum_{|\alpha| \le k} \|D^\alpha f\|_{L^2}^2 \right)^{1/2}.

The inclusion H^k \hookrightarrow L^2 is continuous, and for a bounded linear differential operator \mathcal{A}: H^k \to L^2 we have \|\mathcal{A} f\|_{L^2} \le \|\mathcal{A}\|_{\text{op}} \|f\|_{H^k}.

A.4 Lie Groups and Symmetry Actions

A Lie group \mathcal{G} is a smooth manifold equipped with a group structure such that multiplication and inversion are smooth maps. A representation of \mathcal{G} on a vector space V is a homomorphism \rho: \mathcal{G} \to \operatorname{GL}(V). A function f: \Omega \to \mathbb{R}^m is \mathcal{G}-invariant if f(g\cdot x) = f(x) for all g\in\mathcal{G}, x\in\Omega. It is covariant if it transforms according to a representation: f(g\cdot x) = \rho(g) f(x).

When a finite group \mathcal{G} acts on a finite set X, the orbit of x is \mathcal{G}x = \{gx \mid g\in\mathcal{G}\}. The fixed set of g is \operatorname{Fix}(g) = \{x \in X \mid gx = x\}. The number of orbits is given by Burnside's lemma:

|X/\mathcal{G}| = \frac{1}{|\mathcal{G}|} \sum_{g\in\mathcal{G}} |\operatorname{Fix}(g)|.

A.5 Markov Chains

A homogeneous Markov chain on a finite state space \mathcal{X} is a sequence of random variables X_t with transition probabilities P(x,y) = \Pr(X_{t+1}=y \mid X_t=x) independent of t. The chain is irreducible if for all x,y there exists n such that P^n(x,y)>0. A state x is absorbing if P(x,x)=1. The hitting time to a set A\subset\mathcal{X} is \tau_A = \min\{t\ge 0 : X_t \in A\}.

Theorem A.1 (Borel–Cantelli). If \{E_t\} are events with \sum_{t=1}^\infty \Pr(E_t) < \infty, then \Pr(\limsup E_t) = 0.

A.6 Assouad Dimension

Let (X,d) be a metric space. For R>0 and r>0, let N(R,r) be the minimum number of balls of radius r needed to cover any ball of radius R. The Assouad dimension of X is

d_A = \inf \left\{ \alpha > 0 \mid \exists C>0 \text{ such that } N(R,r) \le C\left(\frac{R}{r}\right)^\alpha \text{ for all } 0<r<R \right\}.

For a finite metric space, the Assouad dimension is finite and satisfies the packing property: the maximum number of points with pairwise distance at least \epsilon is at most C \epsilon^{-d_A} for some constant C.

A.7 Stochastic Approximation

A stochastic approximation algorithm for minimizing a function f(\theta) has the form

\theta_{t+1} = \theta_t - \gamma_t \nabla f(\theta_t) + \eta_t,

where \{\gamma_t\} is a step‑size sequence and \{\eta_t\} is a martingale difference noise. Under the Robbins‑Monro conditions

\sum_{t=1}^\infty \gamma_t = \infty,\qquad \sum_{t=1}^\infty \gamma_t^2 < \infty,

and suitable regularity of f, the sequence \theta_t converges almost surely to a local minimum of f.

