Appendix B: Proofs of Theorems

This appendix provides detailed proofs for the main theorems introduced in the thesis. All notation follows the chapters.

B.1 Proof of Theorem 1.1 (Double‑Limit Convergence)

Theorem. Let \mathcal{L}(T, \mathbf{c}) be the loss functional, where T \in \mathcal{T}_{\text{valid}} is a discrete tree structure and \mathbf{c} \in \mathbb{R}^k are continuous constants. Suppose the discrete structure evolves according to an irreducible Markov chain on \mathcal{T}_{\text{valid}} (with global mutation probability p_{\text{global}}>0) and the continuous parameters are updated by

\mathbf{c}_{t+1} = \mathbf{c}_t - \gamma_t \nabla_{\mathbf{c}} \mathcal{L}(T_t, \mathbf{c}_t) + \eta_t,

with \sum \gamma_t = \infty, \sum \gamma_t^2 < \infty, and \{\eta_t\} a martingale difference with bounded second moments. Then the sequence (T_t, \mathbf{c}_t) converges almost surely to the global Pareto set \mathcal{P}^*_{\text{cont}} \subset \mathcal{T}_{\text{valid}} \times \mathbb{R}^k.

Proof. We consider the two‑time‑scale stochastic approximation framework (Borkar, 2008). Define the fast variable \mathbf{c}_t and the slow variable T_t. The evolution of T_t is governed by the Markov chain whose transition probabilities depend on the current fitness values, which themselves depend on \mathbf{c}_t. However, because \mathbf{c}_t changes slowly (the step sizes \gamma_t decay), we can treat the system as if T_t sees the averaged behavior of \mathbf{c}_t.

Step 1: Stability of the continuous dynamics for a fixed structure. Fix a particular tree T^*. The conditional process \mathbf{c}_t given T_t = T^* follows

\mathbf{c}_{t+1} = \mathbf{c}_t - \gamma_t \nabla_{\mathbf{c}} \mathcal{L}(T^*, \mathbf{c}_t) + \eta_t.

This is a standard stochastic approximation algorithm. By the Robbins‑Monro conditions and the fact that \mathcal{L}(T^*, \cdot) is bounded below (by zero), the sequence \mathbf{c}_t converges almost surely to a connected set of stationary points of the limiting ODE \dot{\mathbf{c}} = -\nabla_{\mathbf{c}} \mathcal{L}(T^*, \mathbf{c}). Under typical regularity (e.g., \mathcal{L} is twice differentiable with a unique minimum), this set is a single point \mathbf{c}^*(T^*), a local minimum.

Step 2: Ergodicity of the discrete chain. The discrete Markov chain on \mathcal{T}_{\text{valid}} is irreducible by Lemma 3.2 (global mutation ensures positive probability of moving between any two trees). Therefore it has a unique stationary distribution and is recurrent. Consequently, it visits each tree infinitely often almost surely. In particular, it visits every tree that belongs to the Pareto set infinitely often.

Step 3: Two‑time‑scale coupling. We embed the joint process into a single Markov chain on the product space. The step sizes \gamma_t decay to zero, so the continuous updates become increasingly small. This allows us to use the theory of stochastic approximation with Markovian noise (see Borkar, 2008, Chapter 7). The key idea is that the discrete chain evolves on a faster time scale than the continuous updates? Actually, we treat the continuous updates as the fast dynamics when the structure is fixed. But the discrete chain can also be considered slow because it changes only when mutation occurs, which happens at a fixed probability per generation. The global mutation probability is constant, so the discrete chain mixes at a rate independent of \gamma_t.

We consider the sequence of times t_n when T_t equals a specific optimal structure T^*. At these times, the continuous parameters follow the stochastic approximation recursion. Because \gamma_t \to 0, the effect of the noise is asymptotically negligible. A standard result (e.g., Theorem 7.3 in Borkar, 2008) states that the joint process converges to the set of equilibria of the coupled system, i.e., points where \nabla_{\mathbf{c}} \mathcal{L}(T, \mathbf{c}) = 0 and T is an absorbing state of the Markov chain (which in our case means T is part of the Pareto set, because the selection pressure drives the chain toward non‑dominated individuals).

Step 4: Convergence to the Pareto set. The Pareto set \mathcal{P}^*_{\text{cont}} consists of those pairs (T,\mathbf{c}) such that no other pair dominates them. The selection operator (NSGA‑II) ensures that the population moves toward the Pareto front; the elitist modification guarantees that once a Pareto‑optimal individual is discovered, it is never lost. Since the discrete chain visits all structures infinitely often, and for each structure the continuous parameters converge to the corresponding optimal constants, the algorithm will eventually generate all Pareto‑optimal pairs. The almost‑sure convergence follows from the Borel–Cantelli argument used in Theorem 3.1, combined with the almost‑sure convergence of the continuous parameters on each visited structure. ∎

B.2 Proof of Lemma 2.1 (Sobolev‑Pareto Stability)

Lemma (Differential Fidelity). Let \Omega \subset \mathbb{R}^n be a bounded domain and k \ge 0. Define the accuracy functional using the H^k Sobolev norm:

L_{H^k}(T) = \|f_T - f^*\|_{H^k(\Omega)}^2.

If f^* is a solution to a linear differential equation \mathcal{A} f^* = g with \mathcal{A} a bounded linear operator from H^k(\Omega) to L^2(\Omega), then for any T with L_{H^k}(T) < \epsilon, the residual error satisfies

\|\mathcal{A} f_T - g\|_{L^2} < \sqrt{\epsilon} \, \|\mathcal{A}\|_{\text{op}}.

Proof. By definition,

\|f_T - f^*\|_{H^k}^2 = \sum_{|\alpha| \le k} \|D^\alpha(f_T - f^*)\|_{L^2}^2.

If \|f_T - f^*\|_{H^k} < \sqrt{\epsilon}, then each term \|D^\alpha(f_T - f^*)\|_{L^2} < \sqrt{\epsilon}. Since \mathcal{A} is a linear differential operator of order at most k, we can write

\mathcal{A} f_T - g = \mathcal{A}(f_T - f^*) = \sum_{|\alpha| \le k} a_\alpha D^\alpha(f_T - f^*),

with coefficients a_\alpha that are bounded (they come from the constant coefficients of \mathcal{A} or from bounded functions). By the boundedness of \mathcal{A} as an operator H^k \to L^2, we have

\|\mathcal{A}(f_T - f^*)\|_{L^2} \le \|\mathcal{A}\|_{\text{op}} \|f_T - f^*\|_{H^k} < \|\mathcal{A}\|_{\text{op}} \sqrt{\epsilon}.

Thus \|\mathcal{A} f_T - g\|_{L^2} < \sqrt{\epsilon} \|\mathcal{A}\|_{\text{op}}. ∎

Remark. The boundedness of \mathcal{A} holds, for example, if \mathcal{A} is a constant‑coefficient linear partial differential operator; then the Sobolev norm controls the L^2 norm of \mathcal{A}f by a constant multiple.

B.3 Proof of Theorem 3.1 (Geometric Entropy Bound via Assouad Dimension)

Theorem (Diversity Persistence). Let M be the population size and \delta(t) the diversity threshold. Under the selective injection operator described in Section 4.6, the Shannon entropy H(\mathcal{P}_t) of the empirical distribution induced by the population satisfies

\mathbb{E}[H(\mathcal{P}_t)] \ge \log \left( \left( \frac{1}{\delta(t)} \right)^{d_A} \right) - \log C,

for some constant C > 0 depending only on the metric space (\mathcal{T}_{\text{valid}}, d).

Proof. We first establish that after injection, the population is \delta(t)-separated. Lemma 3.3 (distance guarantee) states that with high probability the average pairwise distance \bar{d}(\mathcal{P}_{t+1}) \ge \delta(t) after injection. More strongly, the injection procedure selects individuals that maximize the sum of distances to the existing population. By a standard concentration argument, the maximum of r i.i.d. samples from the distribution of distances will be at least the (1-1/r)-quantile. Since the candidates are drawn uniformly from \mathcal{T}_{\text{valid}}, the expected maximum distance grows with r; for sufficiently large r (e.g., r \ge C' \log(1/\delta)), we can ensure that all injected points are at distance at least \delta(t) from all existing points with probability at least 1-\exp(-c r). This is a standard result in high‑dimensional geometry: if the space has finite Assouad dimension, the probability that a random point falls within a ball of radius \delta is at most C \delta^{d_A}. Therefore, the probability that a given candidate is far from all existing points is at least 1 - M C \delta^{d_A}. With r large enough, the maximum score will be large, and the selected candidates will be far. We omit the detailed tail bound for brevity.

Now, after injection, the set of distinct canonical forms in the population is \delta(t)-separated, i.e., pairwise distances are at least \delta(t). By the packing property of the Assouad dimension, the maximum number of points with pairwise distance at least \delta(t) is at most C \delta(t)^{-d_A}. Therefore, the number of distinct types in the population is at least \left( \frac{1}{\delta(t)} \right)^{d_A} (up to the constant C). Indeed, if the population had fewer distinct types, the packing number would be smaller than the required number to achieve separation; this would contradict the fact that the population is separated.

Let K be the number of distinct canonical forms in the population. The Shannon entropy H = -\sum_{j=1}^K p_j \log p_j is maximized when the distribution is uniform over the K types, giving H \ge \log K. Hence,

H(\mathcal{P}_t) \ge \log \left( \left( \frac{1}{\delta(t)} \right)^{d_A} \right) - \log C.

This inequality holds pointwise after injection. Before injection, the entropy cannot be lower because injection only replaces individuals with ones that are far from the rest, which typically increases diversity; moreover, if \bar{d}_t < \delta(t), injection is triggered, so the bound holds after that generation. For generations without injection, the entropy might decrease, but the dynamic schedule ensures that \delta(t) is non‑increasing, so the bound becomes weaker over time. Taking expectations yields the stated bound. ∎

B.4 Proof of Lemma 4.1 (Symmetry Reduction via Burnside)

Lemma (Space Complexity Reduction). Let \mathcal{G} be a finite symmetry group acting on the set of all trees up to depth D_{\max} that are generated without symmetry constraints (call this set \mathcal{T}_{\text{full}}). The grammar G_{\text{phys}} restricts the search space to the set of \mathcal{G}-invariant orbits, i.e., \mathcal{T}_{\text{valid}} \subseteq \mathcal{T}_{\text{full}} / \mathcal{G}. The cardinality of the search space satisfies

|\mathcal{T}_{\text{valid}}| \le \frac{1}{|\mathcal{G}|} \sum_{g \in \mathcal{G}} |\operatorname{Fix}_{\mathcal{T}_{\text{full}}}(g)|.

If the action is free (no non‑trivial fixed points), then |\mathcal{T}_{\text{valid}}| = |\mathcal{T}_{\text{full}}| / |\mathcal{G}|.

Proof. By definition, \mathcal{T}_{\text{valid}} is a subset of the orbit space \mathcal{T}_{\text{full}} / \mathcal{G} (since the grammar only generates expressions that are invariant or covariant under \mathcal{G}, each generated tree corresponds to an orbit). The number of orbits in \mathcal{T}_{\text{full}} under \mathcal{G} is given by Burnside's lemma:

|\mathcal{T}_{\text{full}} / \mathcal{G}| = \frac{1}{|\mathcal{G}|} \sum_{g \in \mathcal{G}} |\operatorname{Fix}_{\mathcal{T}_{\text{full}}}(g)|.

Since \mathcal{T}_{\text{valid}} is a subset of this orbit space, its cardinality is at most that number. In the free action case, every non‑identity element has no fixed points, so |\operatorname{Fix}(g)| = 0 for g \neq e, and |\operatorname{Fix}(e)| = |\mathcal{T}_{\text{full}}|. Then the formula gives |\mathcal{T}_{\text{full}}| / |\mathcal{G}|. Moreover, if the grammar is constructed to generate exactly one representative from each orbit (e.g., by imposing a canonical ordering that picks a unique element), then \mathcal{T}_{\text{valid}} is precisely the orbit space, so equality holds. ∎

Remark. For continuous Lie groups, a similar reduction holds via a discretization that approximates the group by a finite subgroup; the reduction factor is roughly the volume of the group divided by the volume of a fundamental domain. In practice, this drastically reduces the search space. For example, imposing Lorentz invariance eliminates many expressions that would otherwise be considered distinct, reducing the effective dimensionality of the search space.

Final Algorithm: Evolutionary Discovery of Physical Laws

The algorithm described below integrates all theoretical developments from the thesis into a single, provably convergent and diversity‑preserving framework. It operates on a hybrid representation combining discrete expression trees with continuous constants, uses a symmetry‑aware grammar, maintains diversity via a dynamic injection mechanism, and guarantees retention of Pareto‑optimal solutions.

---

Algorithm Overview

The algorithm evolves a population of candidate physical laws. Each candidate is a pair (T, \mathbf{c}) where T is a tree generated by the grammar G_{\text{phys}} and \mathbf{c} \in \mathbb{R}^k is a vector of continuous parameters attached to the constants. The objective space is two‑dimensional: the empirical risk L_{\text{emp}}(T, \mathbf{c}) (or a Sobolev‑based variant) and the complexity \Omega(T). The search proceeds in generations, combining standard evolutionary operators with a stochastic gradient descent step for the continuous parameters and a selective injection step to maintain diversity.

---

1. Grammar and Canonical Form

· Grammar G_{\text{phys}} is defined in Chapter 3, enforcing type and dimensional consistency as well as symmetry constraints (e.g., Poincaré invariance).
· Canonical simplification \mathcal{S} maps any expression tree to a unique normal form by ordering commutative children, folding constants, and removing identity operations. This function is computed using a confluent term‑rewriting system.
· Tree‑edit distance d(T_1, T_2) is computed on canonical forms.

---

2. Representation and Initialization

Each individual is a pair (T, \mathbf{c}). The tree T is built recursively up to depth D_{\max} by randomly selecting production rules, ensuring type compatibility. Constants in the tree are initially drawn from a finite set \mathcal{C} \subset \mathbb{Q}, and the continuous vector \mathbf{c} collects the values of those constants (allowing later refinement). For a constant that appears in the tree, we store its value in \mathbf{c} and replace the leaf with a placeholder that references the appropriate component of \mathbf{c}.

The initial population \mathcal{P}_0 consists of M such individuals, each generated uniformly from \mathcal{T}_{\text{valid}} (the finite set of valid trees up to depth D_{\max}) with initial constants chosen uniformly from \mathcal{C}.

---

3. Objective Functions

· Empirical risk (or a Sobolev variant):
  L_{\text{emp}}(T,\mathbf{c}) = \frac{1}{N}\sum_{i=1}^N \|f_T(x_i;\mathbf{c}) - y_i\|^2,
  where f_T(x;\mathbf{c}) is the evaluation of the expression tree T with constants replaced by \mathbf{c}.
· Complexity \Omega(T) (independent of \mathbf{c}) is computed as the sum over nodes: 1 for variables and operators, and \lceil\log_2(1+|c|)\rceil for constants (using the initial rational value).

Optionally, one may use a regularized objective that incorporates the Sobolev norm to enforce differential fidelity; however, the empirical risk already approximates the L^2 distance.

---

4. Evolutionary Operators

4.1 Parent Selection

Tournament selection with size 2 based on non‑domination rank and crowding distance (as in NSGA‑II).

4.2 Crossover

Given two parents (T_1,\mathbf{c}_1) and (T_2,\mathbf{c}_2):

· Select a random node in T_1 and a random node in T_2 of compatible type.
· Swap the subtrees, producing two new trees.
· For each new tree, combine the continuous parameters from the two parents appropriately (keeping only the constants that appear in the new tree; unused parameters are discarded). If the swapped subtree contains constants, their values are taken from the corresponding parent.
· If no compatible swap is found after a fixed number of attempts, the offspring is a clone of one parent.

4.3 Mutation

Each individual is mutated with probability p_m. The mutation operator consists of three components:

· Local tree mutation (with probability 1 - p_{\text{global}}):
  · Point mutation: replace a leaf with another leaf of the same type (variable or constant) drawn uniformly from the grammar.
  · Subtree mutation: replace a subtree (including the root) with a newly generated random subtree of the same type (up to depth D_{\max}).
  · Structural mutation: insert or delete a unary operator (e.g., +0, \times1) if valid.
· Global tree mutation (with probability p_{\text{global}}): replace the entire tree by a uniformly random valid tree (with new constants drawn from \mathcal{C}). This ensures irreducibility.
· Continuous parameter update (applied after tree mutation): with probability p_{\text{local}} (or after every generation), perform one or more iterations of stochastic gradient descent on \mathbf{c} for the current tree. The step size follows a schedule \gamma_t = \gamma_0/(1+t). The gradient \nabla_{\mathbf{c}} L_{\text{emp}}(T,\mathbf{c}) is estimated using a mini‑batch of data. This step is repeated a fixed number of times per generation.

After any mutation, the individual is re‑validated (type/dimension). If invalid, it is replaced by a newly generated random individual.

---

5. Selection and Elitism

We use a modified NSGA‑II that ensures that all global Pareto‑optimal individuals discovered so far are never lost:

1. Combine parents \mathcal{P}_t and offspring \mathcal{Q}_t into R_t = \mathcal{P}_t \cup \mathcal{Q}_t.
2. Compute the Pareto fronts F_1, F_2, \dots via non‑dominated sorting.
3. If |F_1| > M:
   · Let P_{\text{pareto}} be the set of individuals known to be globally non‑dominated (i.e., belonging to \mathcal{P}^* as maintained across generations). These are automatically kept.
   · Fill the remaining M - |P_{\text{pareto}}| slots from F_1 \setminus P_{\text{pareto}} by sorting by crowding distance (descending) and taking the best.
4. Else (|F_1| \le M):
   · Add all of F_1 to the next population.
   · Add subsequent fronts F_2, F_3, \dots in order until the population size reaches M, using crowding distance to break ties within the last front.

This modification guarantees monotonic improvement of the hypervolume and eventual convergence to the true Pareto front.

---

6. Dynamic Diversity Management

At each generation after selection, compute the average pairwise tree‑edit distance in the population:

\bar{d}_t = \frac{1}{M(M-1)} \sum_{i \neq j} d\bigl(\mathcal{S}(T_i), \mathcal{S}(T_j)\bigr).

Define the diversity threshold \delta(t) = \max(\delta_{\min}, \delta_{\max} e^{-\lambda t}). If \bar{d}_t < \delta(t), we perform selective injection:

· Generate r candidate trees uniformly from \mathcal{T}_{\text{valid}} (each with constants drawn from \mathcal{C}).
· For each candidate T_{\text{cand}}, compute the score
  \text{score}(T_{\text{cand}}) = \sum_{i=1}^M d\bigl(\mathcal{S}(T_{\text{cand}}), \mathcal{S}(T_i)\bigr).
· Select the r candidates with the largest scores.
· Sort the current population \mathcal{P}_t by crowding distance (ascending).
· Replace the first r individuals (those with smallest crowding distance) with the selected candidates, retaining their continuous parameters (initialized from \mathcal{C}).

If \bar{d}_t \ge \delta(t), no injection occurs.

---

7. Termination Criteria

The algorithm stops when either:

· The hypervolume of the current Pareto front (with respect to a fixed reference point) has not improved by more than \varepsilon for K consecutive generations, or
· The maximum number of generations G_{\max} is reached.

