10. Complexity Considerations

· Validity checking (type/dimension) can be done in O(|T|) time.
· Canonical simplification \mathcal{S} is computed using a rewriting system that terminates in O(|T|) for fixed operator set.
· Tree‑edit distance between two trees of size at most D_{\max} can be computed in O(D_{\max}^3) using standard dynamic programming, but we apply it only on canonical forms and after injection, which occurs only when diversity is low; the total cost remains manageable for moderate D_{\max}.
· Gradient descent on continuous parameters requires evaluating the expression tree and its derivatives; this can be done via automatic differentiation in O(|T|) per step.
· The algorithm is designed for moderate problem sizes (D_{\max} \le 10, M \le 100) and can be parallelized across individuals.

